Learn more about PurePitch<sup>=C2=AE</sup> Next Generation Homebrew</stron=
g></a></h4>
<p style=3D"font-size: 16px;"><span style=3D"color: #212529;">A yeast start=
er can be helpful as it allows you to<span style=3D"font-weight: bold;"> en=
sure your yeast is in an active state</span> when pitching and will <span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: bold;">generally lead to a shorter lag time.</span></s=
pan></p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 16px;"><span style=3D"color: #212529;"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: normal;"> We created <a href=3D"https://www.whitelabs.com/=
research-development" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">PurePitch<sup>=C2=
=AE</sup> Next Generation</a> Homebrew for ease of use for you!</span><span=
 style=3D"font-weight: bold;"> Use the entire pouch for a Professional reco=
mmendation of an Ale Pitch rate (0.75 million cells/mL) per 5 gallons. </sp=
an><span style=3D"font-weight: normal;">Or aseptically</span><span style=3D=
"font-weight: bold;"> use some of the pouches for a starter </span><span st=
yle=3D"font-weight: normal;">and</span><span style=3D"font-weight: bold;"> =
save some for later use up until the best-by date.</span></span></p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 18px;"><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/hs-fs/=
hubfs/PurePitch%20Next%20Generation%20Homebrew%20Use%20Now%20or%20Later.jpg=
?width=3D500&amp;height=3D625&amp;name=3DPurePitch%20Next%20Generation%20Ho=
mebrew%20Use%20Now%20or%20Later.jpg" width=3D"500" height=3D"625" loading=
=3D"lazy" alt=3D"PurePitch Next Generation Homebrew Use Now or Later" style=
=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 500px; margin-left: auto; margin-=
right: auto; display: block;"><span style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 16p=
x;">Follow along while we break down a step-by-step process of making a sta=
rter.</span></p>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Step 1:=
 Gather Your Supplies</strong></h4>
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 16px;">
<li>150 grams of DME (Dry Malt Extract)</li>
<li>One 2-liter flask</li>
<li>Stir Plate</li>
<li>Stir Bar</li>
<li>Sanitizer&nbsp;</li>
<li>Yeast</li>
</ul>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Step 2:=
 Sanitize</strong></h4>
<p style=3D"font-weight: normal; font-size: 16px;"><span style=3D"color: #2=
12529;">Sanitization is key when it comes to handling yeast and making star=
ters and beer. A starter is full of nutrients your yeast (and any other mic=
roorganisms) need to replicate and begin metabolism which means if there ar=
e any other contaminating organisms present, it=E2=80=99s likely to become =
a problem when fermenting your beer.&nbsp;</span><br><br><span style=3D"col=
or: #212529;">There are <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">many food-grade =
and no-rinse sanitizers such as StarSan</span>. Check your local homebrew s=
hop to see what=E2=80=99s available.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Step 3:=
 Boil DME</strong></h4>
<p style=3D"font-weight: normal; font-size: 16px;"><span style=3D"color: #2=
12529;">Boil <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">150 grams of dry malt extra=
ct</span> in <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">1.5 liter of water</span> a=
iming for about <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">1.037 Specific Gravity</=
span>. Be cautious of scorching the extract as you bring to a boil and allo=
w the solids to dissolve fully. You may choose to add additional yeast nutr=
ients such as&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: #212529;"><a href=3D"https:=
//www.whitelabs.com/enzymes-nutrients-detail?id=3D4&amp;type=3DENZYMENUTRIE=
NT" style=3D"color: #ea7600;">White Labs Yeast Nutrient</a></span><span sty=
le=3D"color: #212529;">&nbsp;or&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: #212529;"=
><a href=3D"https://www.whitelabs.com/enzymes-nutrients-detail?id=3D6&amp;t=
ype=3DENZYMENUTRIENT" style=3D"color: #ea7600;">Servomyces</a></span><span =
style=3D"color: #212529;">&nbsp;at this stage as well.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p style=3D"font-weight: normal;"><span style=3D"color: #212529; font-size:=
 16px;"><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Purepitch%20Next=
%20Generation%20Homebrew%20Shot%202.jpg?width=3D800&amp;height=3D534&amp;na=
me=3DPurepitch%20Next%20Generation%20Homebrew%20Shot%202.jpg" width=3D"800"=
 height=3D"534" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Purepitch Next Generation Homebrew =
Shot 2" style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 800px; margin-left: =
auto; margin-right: auto; display: block;"></span></p>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Step 4:=
 Cool and Add Yeast</strong></h4>
<p style=3D"font-weight: normal;"><span style=3D"font-size: 16px;">Ensure t=
he solution is<span style=3D"font-weight: bold;"> cooled to room temperatur=
e</span>. Once cooled, as aseptically as possible, add the yeast. A<span st=
yle=3D"font-weight: bold;"> spray bottle of isopropanol or StarSan is sugge=
sted to spray down any surfaces or materials that may come into contact wit=
h yeast,&nbsp; including your hands or gloves</span>.</span>&nbsp;</p>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Step 5:=
 Cover Flask and Turn on Stir Plate</strong></h4>
<p style=3D"font-size: 16px;"><span>In this step, you want to ensure the ye=
ast <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">continues to get a healthy dose of o=
xygen and remain aerobic</span>. This will allow the yeast to <span style=
=3D"font-weight: bold;">build their cell walls and prepare for the stressfu=
l environment of fermentation. </span></span></p>
<p style=3D"font-size: 16px;"><span>Make sure the <span style=3D"font-weigh=
t: bold;">flask cover is loose</span> to promote gas exchange. <span style=
=3D"font-weight: bold;">Allow your starter to stir for 24 hours, and then p=
itch directly to your full volume of wort.</span> You <span style=3D"font-w=
eight: bold;">may also refrigerate and then decant</span> but it=E2=80=99s =
recommended to use your starter as quickly as possible.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Stir%20Plate.pn=
g?width=3D800&amp;height=3D701&amp;name=3DStir%20Plate.png" width=3D"800" h=
eight=3D"701" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Stir Plate" style=3D"height: auto; ma=
x-width: 100%; width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; display=
: block;"></span></p>
<h4 style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 1.5rem !important;"><strong>Tips:</=
strong></h4>
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 18px;">
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 18px;">
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 18px;">
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 18px;">
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 18px;">
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 16px;">
<li aria-level=3D"1">Use a <a href=3D"https://yeastman.com/calculator" rel=
=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">yeast calculator</a> for an estimated pitch=
 rates.</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">A stir plate can increase the growth rate of your yeas=
t, but it's not strictly necessary. You can also shake the flask periodical=
ly to keep the yeast in suspension.</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">If you're reusing yeast from a previous batch, sanitiz=
e any equipment that will come into contact with the yeast to avoid contami=
nation.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></li>
</ul>
</ul>
</ul>
</ul>
</ul>
</ul>
<h5 style=3D"text-align: center;"><a href=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/cel=
l-counting-your-yeast-culture" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank"><strong>L=
earn How to Cell Count</strong></a></h5>
<p style=3D"text-align: center; font-size: 16px;">While a yeast starter may=
 not be necessary with lab-grown yeast, it can be a fun way to manage your =
